00:05:46.399 --> 00:05:53.679
but when I have a PDF output, so for the printed book, I actually want to make an index, so I tag

00:05:53.679 --> 00:06:00.079
that. And then, in addition to tagging this throughout, which is a manual process that you

00:06:00.079 --> 00:06:05.200
as the author are going to want to do, the things that you want in your index, you then write a

00:06:05.200 --> 00:06:12.320
tech file that is going to be included at the end of the processing of your PDF that basically says

00:06:12.320 --> 00:06:18.160
in the back matter, print index, and then your Corta YAML gives you a place to declare that as

00:06:18.160 --> 00:06:26.720
well. It says, let's include that after the body and create our index. Then, when you render to PDF,

00:06:26.720 --> 00:06:31.920
Corta will actually take a little bit longer and render things twice to get the page references

00:06:31.920 --> 00:06:40.079
correctly for all your index calls. All right, well, that was all nice, but what I am looking

00:06:40.079 --> 00:06:45.600
forward to, and I have the, you know, luxury of giving this talk towards the end of the conference, is

