Now, Korto allows you to write, for example, alternative text for your figures, and the best

00:08:18.640 --> 00:08:23.600
practice is that as you create your plot, you write the alternative text at the time of writing

00:08:23.600 --> 00:08:28.799
the caption or whatever else. And then what happens is when you are actually reading this

00:08:28.799 --> 00:08:34.880
book in the browser, the screen reader, to the screen reader, this accessible text, the alternative

00:08:34.880 --> 00:08:42.159
text is accessible to it, and it reads it out loud for you. Unfortunately, I hate to admit, particularly

00:08:42.159 --> 00:08:47.679
because this was a second edition of a book, at times I've gotten sloppy and maybe forgotten to

00:08:47.679 --> 00:08:55.200
add these in a few places. Then I look to see how many places, how do I make sure that all of the

00:08:55.200 --> 00:09:01.840
figures have alternative text. Well, it looks like every single plot is created with ggplot in this

00:09:01.840 --> 00:09:08.239
book. So if I search on GitHub, there are 46 files that have ggplot calls in them, and actually

00:09:08.239 --> 00:09:16.080
there's about 419 references to ggplot. So I'm definitely not going to manually go through each

00:09:16.080 --> 00:09:22.320
and every one of these cells. So what I'm about to show you is not a package, is not even necessarily

