a single function, but a snippet of code that you can make use to sort of parse your QMD file. So

00:09:28.719 --> 00:09:37.840
the package I'm going to leverage here is parsermd. I'm going to use that to, once I read my QMD file,

00:09:37.840 --> 00:09:43.440
and note that I've broken one of my QMD files from my chapter to remove one of the alternative

00:09:43.440 --> 00:09:50.960
texts so that we can get an alert when something is missing. I pipe that into the parseQMD function,

00:09:50.960 --> 00:09:59.039
which basically splits it into the markdown text and the code. And then I'm looking for anything

00:09:59.039 --> 00:10:07.599
that is a code chunk that basically matches ggplot2 in its contents and does not have the option

00:10:07.599 --> 00:10:14.239
fig out. Then I can ask it to give me the label for that. I do meticulously label all of my code

00:10:14.239 --> 00:10:19.840
cells, so this is good enough generally for me to go back and add that. But if you haven't done so,

00:10:19.840 --> 00:10:25.520
you can also say give me the contents of that code cell, and then you can just sort of

00:10:25.520 --> 00:10:32.239
like control F in your document to find them. I think in a future iteration, I'd maybe like to

00:10:32.239 --> 00:10:37.679
turn all of this into a function and maybe even have it be automatically checked every time I push

00:10:37.679 --> 00:10:42.960
my files to GitHub. But at least the tooling is there for you to be able to check for these things.

